2026-03-26 | Number of Ways to Reach Destination in Shortest Time

	Question
Return the number of shortest paths from node 0 to node V-1.

	Approach
1.	Use **Dijkstra’s Algorithm** to find shortest distances.
2.	Maintain:
		dist[i] → shortest distance to node i  
		ways[i] → number of ways to reach node i  

3.	Initialization:
		dist[0] = 0  
		ways[0] = 1  

4.	While processing edges:
	- If new shorter path found:
			dist[v] = newDist  
			ways[v] = ways[u]  
	- If same shortest path found:
			ways[v] += ways[u]

5.	Answer:
		ways[V-1]

	(Time modulo 1e9+7 if needed)

	Time Complexity
	O((V + E) log V)

	Space Complexity
	O(V + E)

	Solution

class Solution {
public:
    int countPaths(int n, vector<vector<int>>& edges) {

        const int MOD = 1e9 + 7;

        vector<vector<pair<int,int>>> adj(n);

        for(auto &e : edges){
            int u = e[0], v = e[1], w = e[2];
            adj[u].push_back({v,w});
            adj[v].push_back({u,w});
        }

        vector<long long> dist(n, LLONG_MAX);
        vector<int> ways(n, 0);

        priority_queue<pair<long long,int>, vector<pair<long long,int>>, greater<>> pq;

        dist[0] = 0;
        ways[0] = 1;
        pq.push({0,0});

        while(!pq.empty()){
            auto [d,u] = pq.top();
            pq.pop();

            if(d > dist[u]) continue;

            for(auto &[v,w] : adj[u]){

                long long newDist = d + w;

                if(newDist < dist[v]){
                    dist[v] = newDist;
                    ways[v] = ways[u];
                    pq.push({newDist, v});
                }
                else if(newDist == dist[v]){
                    ways[v] = (ways[v] + ways[u]) % MOD;
                }
            }
        }

        return ways[n-1];
    }
};

	Key Insight
We extend Dijkstra by tracking **number of shortest paths**.  
Whenever we find another path with equal shortest distance, we **add ways instead of replacing**.
